{{also|abjuré}}
==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abjuren|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abiūrō||deny upon oath}} (possibly via {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|abiurer|abjurer|lang=frm}}), formed from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{m|la|iūro||swear or take an oath}}, from {{m|la|iūs||law, right, duty}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=3}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈdʒʊɹ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abjure.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʊə(ɹ)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abjur}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[renounce]] upon [[oath]]; to [[forswear]]; to [[disavow]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
#: ''To abjure allegiance to a prince.''
#: ''To abjure the realm'' (to swear to abandon it forever).
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|historical|lang=en}} To cause one to renounce or recant. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[reject]] with [[solemnity]]; to abandon [[forever]]; to [[repudiate]]; to [[disclaim]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''To abjure errors.''
#* '''1610''', ''[[s:The Tempest|The Tempest]]'', by [[w:William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]], act 5 scene 1
#*: But this rough magic I here '''abjure''' [...]
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To abstain from; to [[avoid]]; to [[shun]].

